## Core theory and syntaxes of control statements
What are Control Statements?

Control statements determine the flow of execution of a program. They allow a program to make decisions, repeat tasks, and transfer control from one part of the code to another.

Types of Control Statements
Selection (Decision-Making) Statements
Iteration (Looping) Statements
Jump Statements
A. Selection Statements
1. if Statement

Used to execute a block of code when a condition is true.

int age = 18;

if(age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("Eligible to vote");
}
2. if-else Statement
int age = 16;

if(age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("Eligible");
} else {
    System.out.println("Not Eligible");
}
3. if-else-if Ladder
int marks = 85;

if(marks >= 90) {
    System.out.println("Grade A");
}
else if(marks >= 75) {
    System.out.println("Grade B");
}
else {
    System.out.println("Grade C");
}
4. Nested if
int age = 20;
boolean hasLicense = true;

if(age >= 18) {
    if(hasLicense) {
        System.out.println("Can drive");
    }
}
5. switch Statement
int day = 3;

switch(day) {
    case 1:
        System.out.println("Monday");
        break;

    case 2:
        System.out.println("Tuesday");
        break;

    case 3:
        System.out.println("Wednesday");
        break;

    default:
        System.out.println("Invalid Day");
}
Modern Switch Expression (Java 14+)
int day = 2;

switch(day) {
    case 1 -> System.out.println("Monday");
    case 2 -> System.out.println("Tuesday");
    default -> System.out.println("Invalid");
}
B. Iteration Statements
1. for Loop
for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    System.out.println(i);
}
2. while Loop
int i = 1;

while(i <= 5) {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
}
3. do-while Loop
int i = 1;

do {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
} while(i <= 5);
4. Enhanced for Loop
int arr[] = {10,20,30,40};

for(int num : arr) {
    System.out.println(num);
}
C. Jump Statements
1. break
for(int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
    if(i == 5)
        break;

    System.out.println(i);
}

Output:

1
2
3
4
2. continue
for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    if(i == 3)
        continue;

    System.out.println(i);
}

Output:

1
2
4
5
3. return
public static int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
| Feature             | if-else               | switch                    |
| ------------------- | --------------------- | ------------------------- |
| Condition           | Boolean expression    | Constant value            |
| Multiple Conditions | Yes                   | Limited                   |
| Readability         | Less for many options | Better                    |
| Performance         | Slightly slower       | Faster for multiple cases |


2. Company-Based Questions on Control Statements
Frequently Asked in Service-Based Companies
Q1. Difference between while and do-while?

Answer:

while	do-while
Condition checked first	Condition checked later
May execute zero times	Executes at least once

Example:

int x = 10;

while(x < 5) {
    System.out.println(x);
}

No output.

do {
    System.out.println(x);
} while(x < 5);

Output:

10
Q2. Can switch work with String?

Answer:

Yes. Since Java 7.

String city = "Delhi";

switch(city) {
    case "Delhi":
        System.out.println("Capital");
        break;
}
Q3. What happens if break is omitted in switch?

Answer:

Control falls through to subsequent cases.

int x = 1;

switch(x) {
    case 1:
        System.out.println("One");

    case 2:
        System.out.println("Two");
}

Output:

One
Two
Q4. Can we use float in switch?

Answer:

No.

Allowed:

byte
short
char
int
String
enum
Integer
Character

Not Allowed:

float
double
long
Q5. Difference between break and continue?

Answer:

break

Terminates loop.

continue

Skips current iteration.

Frequently Asked in Product-Based Companies
Q6. Predict Output
for(int i=0;i<5;i++) {
    if(i==3)
        break;

    System.out.print(i+" ");
}

Output:

0 1 2
Q7. Predict Output
for(int i=0;i<5;i++) {
    if(i==2)
        continue;

    System.out.print(i+" ");
}

Output:

0 1 3 4
Q8. Infinite Loop Examples
for(;;) {
    System.out.println("Hello");
}

or

while(true) {
}
Q9. Which Loop is Best When Number of Iterations is Known?

Answer:

for loop

Reason:

Initialization, condition, and increment are in one place.

Q10. Which Loop is Best When Iterations are Unknown?

Answer:

while loop

Example:

while(userInput != password) {
}




3. Interview Questions and Answers
Beginner Level
Q1. What are control statements?

Answer:

Control statements alter the normal execution flow of a program. They are categorized into:

Decision-making
Iteration
Jump statements
Q2. What are decision-making statements in Java?

Answer:

if
if-else
if-else-if
nested if
switch
Q3. What is a loop?

Answer:

A loop repeatedly executes a block of code until a condition becomes false.

Q4. Name all loops in Java.

Answer:

for
while
do-while
enhanced for
Q5. Which loop executes at least once?

Answer:

do-while
Intermediate Level
Q6. Can we write an if statement without braces?

Answer:

Yes, for a single statement.

if(x > 0)
    System.out.println("Positive");
Q7. Can switch have duplicate cases?

Answer:

No.

switch(x) {
    case 1:
    case 1:
}

Compile-time error.

Q8. Can break be used outside loops?

Answer:

No.

It can only be used inside:

loops
switch statements
Q9. What is fall-through in switch?

Answer:

Execution continues into the next case when break is absent.

Q10. What is the purpose of default in switch?

Answer:

Executes when no case matches.

Advanced Level
Q11. What is a labeled break?
outer:
for(int i=0;i<3;i++) {

    for(int j=0;j<3;j++) {

        if(i==1 && j==1)
            break outer;
    }
}

Answer:

Exits multiple nested loops at once.

Q12. What is a labeled continue?
outer:
for(int i=0;i<3;i++) {

    for(int j=0;j<3;j++) {

        if(j==1)
            continue outer;

        System.out.println(i+" "+j);
    }
}

Answer:

Skips to the next iteration of the labeled outer loop.

Q13. Which loop is more efficient?

Answer:

No loop is inherently faster. Efficiency depends on the logic and compiler optimizations.

Q14. What is the difference between == and equals() in conditions?

Answer:

==

Compares references (or primitive values).

equals()

Compares object content.

Example:

String a = new String("Java");
String b = new String("Java");

System.out.println(a == b);       // false
System.out.println(a.equals(b));  // true
Q15. Write a program to print numbers 1 to 100 without using a loop.
class Test {

    static void print(int n) {

        if(n <= 100) {
            System.out.println(n);
            print(n + 1);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        print(1);
    }
}

Concept: Recursion instead of iteration.

